  "description": "Orientation refers to whether a tarot card appears upright or reversed (upside-down) when revealed in a spread. In traditions that read reversals, a reversed card modifies the card\u0026rsquo;s meaning — typically by introducing delay, internalization, blockage, or the shadow side of the card\u0026rsquo;s upright theme.\nNot all readers use reversals. Some traditions read all cards upright, treating the card\u0026rsquo;s position in the spread and its relationship to neighboring cards as sufficient for nuance. Others treat reversals as essential, arguing that without them the deck can only speak in one register and loses half its expressive range.\n",
